{
  "answer": "In the Old English elegy known as *The Ruin* (the opening \"Wraetlic is þes wealstan\"), the bath-houses (*bæþ-hus*) are first evoked amid the lost splendor of the city,[^1] then described in evocative detail toward the end: a hot stream surges within enclosing walls, pouring \"hot streams\" over grey stone into the pool.[^2]\n\n[^1]: Old English Elegies, ch. 16 (*Wraetlic is þes wealstan...*), [p-ba51da](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/16-wraetlic-is-thes-wealstan-wyrde-yebraecon-burgsted/translation/#p-ba51da).\n\n[^2]: Old English Elegies, ch. 16 (*Wraetlic is þes wealstan...*), [p-dfdbda](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/16-wraetlic-is-thes-wealstan-wyrde-yebraecon-burgsted/translation/#p-dfdbda).",
